The highly green fluorescent CL-C dots attractive materials for anti-counterfeiting, information encryption and information storage. The process for making anti-counterfeit fluorescent ink is described in the experimental section 2.6. Anti-counterfeiting fluorescent ink was filled in a marker then used for drawing, writing on the Whatman No.1 filter paper (Figs. 5, 6

                        ). The information such as “carbon dots, clean and green earth” (Fig. 5.) and Fig. 6(B) “information icon, barcode, save our souls (SOS) symbols, wear face mask symbol” “Dr. NV LAB and BSARCIST” was written on whatman filter paper by using fluorescent ink. Photographs of all the information and symbols have taken under day and UV-light (Figs. 5, 6 (A,B)). Fig. 7
                         shows day light and UV light photographs of Anti-Counterfeiting fluorescence ink coated bank currency notes. Anti-Counterfeiting fluorescence ink filled marker was used to draw lines and circle on the bank currency notes (Artificial currency notes). Under UV light, all of the green fluorescent symbols and information were clearly visible, and were invisible during the day.
